new='PASSAGES["Level 21"]=[{title:"The Mystery of Consciousness",text:"Consciousness — the subjective experience of being aware, of having an inner life, of knowing what it feels like to see red or taste coffee — is arguably the most profound unsolved problem in science. We can describe the neural correlates of consciousness: the brain activity that accompanies particular experiences. We can identify brain regions whose damage disrupts awareness. We can measure the electrical signatures of wakefulness and sleep. What we cannot do is explain why any of this physical activity is accompanied by subjective experience at all. Philosopher David Chalmers called this the hard problem of consciousness, distinguishing it from the comparatively easier problems of explaining cognitive functions and behaviours. The hard problem asks why there is something it is like to be a conscious creature rather than nothing — why the processing of visual information by the brain is accompanied by the experience of seeing rather than occurring in the dark. Several competing theories attempt to address this. Integrated Information Theory, proposed by neuroscientist Giulio Tononi, suggests that consciousness is a property of systems that integrate information in particular ways and can in principle be quantified. Global Workspace Theory proposes that consciousness arises when information is broadcast widely across the brain rather than remaining localized. Some philosophers argue that consciousness may be a fundamental feature of the universe, like mass or charge, rather than something that emerges from physical complexity. The question remains genuinely open, and some researchers argue it may be permanently beyond human understanding — a limit set not by current ignorance but by the structure of the human mind itself.",qs:["What distinguishes the hard problem of consciousness from easier problems?","How do Integrated Information Theory and Global Workspace Theory differ in their approaches?","What does it mean to say consciousness might be a fundamental feature of the universe?","What does it suggest about science if some questions may be permanently beyond human understanding?"]},{title:"How Evolution Works",text:"Evolution by natural selection is one of the most powerful and most misunderstood ideas in science. Its core logic is straightforward: individuals within a population vary in their heritable traits. Some variants are better suited to current environmental conditions and therefore survive and reproduce more successfully than others. Because traits are heritable, successful variants become more common in subsequent generations. Over many generations this process can produce dramatic change — new species, new body plans, new behaviours — from nothing more than variation, heredity, and differential reproduction. The mechanism that produces heritable variation is mutation: random errors or changes in DNA that occur during replication or in response to environmental factors. Most mutations are neutral or harmful and are eliminated or remain rare. A small fraction improve the organism\'s fit to its environment and are favoured by selection. Evolution has no direction, no goal, and no foresight. It does not produce perfect organisms — it produces organisms that are good enough to survive and reproduce in current conditions. Features that were adaptive in past environments can become liabilities when conditions change. The human spine, which evolved for a creature that walked on four limbs, is poorly suited to upright bipedal walking and produces the chronic back pain that afflicts a majority of adults at some point. Common misconceptions include the idea that evolution moves toward complexity — it does not, and many successful evolutionary lineages have moved toward simplicity — and the idea that individuals evolve. Evolution acts on populations over generations, not on individuals within a lifetime.",qs:["What three conditions are necessary for natural selection to occur?","Why does evolution produce organisms that are good enough rather than perfect?","What does the human spine example illustrate about evolution?","What are two common misconceptions about evolution that the passage addresses?"]},{title:"The Nature of Time",text:"Time is so woven into human experience that questioning its nature can seem almost nonsensical. And yet time has proven to be one of the most puzzling concepts in physics, and our everyday intuitions about it are wrong in ways that have been experimentally confirmed. Isaac Newton conceived of time as absolute — a universal river flowing at the same rate everywhere, providing the backdrop against which all events occur. Einstein\'s special theory of relativity, published in 1905, replaced this picture with something far stranger. Time, Einstein showed, is not absolute but relative: it passes at different rates depending on velocity and gravity. This is not a philosophical claim but a measurable physical fact. Atomic clocks flown on aircraft tick slightly faster than identical clocks on the ground because they experience less gravitational pull. Astronauts returning from the International Space Station have aged very slightly less than people who remained on Earth. At velocities approaching the speed of light, time dilation becomes dramatic — a traveller moving at ninety-nine percent of light speed would age only about one seventh as fast as a stationary observer. The direction of time — the fact that it flows from past to future rather than the reverse — is one of the deepest puzzles in physics. The fundamental laws of physics are time-symmetric: they work equally well run forward or backward. The apparent one-directionality of time, called the arrow of time, is thought to be connected to entropy, the tendency of systems to move from ordered to disordered states, but a complete explanation remains elusive.",qs:["How did Einstein\'s conception of time differ from Newton\'s?","What experimental evidence confirms that time passes at different rates in different conditions?","What is the arrow of time and why is it puzzling given the laws of physics?","What does the malleability of time suggest about the reliability of human intuition as a guide to understanding reality?"]}];\n'
